Then add Bootstrap CSS (and JS if needed) in the angular.json file under:
"styles" array
"scripts" array
âœ… This is the recommended approach because:
It is easy to manage.
It works well with Angular CLI.
It keeps project dependencies organized.
2ï¸âƒ£ Using CDN (Content Delivery Network)
Instead of installing locally, we can directly add Bootstrap links in the index.html file.
Add Bootstrap CSS and JS links inside <head> or before closing <body>.
âœ… This method:
Is quick and simple.
Does not require installation.
But is not preferred for production because it depends on an external network.

Que 36) How can you pass data between components in Angular?
-------------------------------------------------------------
In Angular, data can be passed between components in three main ways:
1ï¸âƒ£ Parent to Child â€“ Using @Input()
The @Input() decorator is used to pass data from parent component to child component.
The parent sends data using property binding.
The child receives data using @Input().
âœ… Example:
Parent HTML:
<app-child [message]="parentMessage"></app-child>
Child Component:
@Input() message: string;
ğŸ‘‰ Used when data flows one-way (parent â†’ child).
2ï¸âƒ£ Child to Parent â€“ Using @Output() and EventEmitter
The @Output() decorator is used to send data from child to parent.
It works with EventEmitter.
âœ… Used when child needs to send events or data back to parent.
3ï¸âƒ£ Using Service (For Unrelated Components)
When components are not directly related (not parent-child),
We use a shared service with observables (like Subject or BehaviorSubject) to share data.
ğŸ‘‰ This is commonly used in large applications.
4ï¸âƒ£ Using Router State / Route Parameters
Data can also be passed while navigating using:
Route parameters
Query parameters
Router state

Que 37) Explain Lazy Loading in Angular ?
------------------------------------------
1ï¸âƒ£ What is Lazy Loading?
Lazy loading means loading modules only when they are needed.
Angular does not load the entire application at once.
It loads some parts later, when the user visits that page.
2ï¸âƒ£ Why is Lazy Loading Used?
To reduce initial loading time.
To improve application performance.
To make the app faster at startup.
3ï¸âƒ£ How Does It Work?
We divide the application into feature modules.
These modules are loaded only when a user navigates to that route.
It is configured in the routing module using loadChildren.
4ï¸âƒ£ Real-Time Example
Suppose your app has:
Home Page, Login Page, Admin Dashboard
When the app starts:
Only Home and basic modules are loaded.
Admin Dashboard loads only when user clicks on Admin.

Que 38) What is MVVM Architecture in Angular?
----------------------------------------------
1ï¸âƒ£ What is MVVM?
MVVM stands for Model â€“ View â€“ ViewModel.
It is a design pattern used to separate UI and business logic.
It helps keep the code clean and organized.
ğŸ”¹ 1. Model
Model represents the data and business logic.
It handles data from:
API
Database
Services
In Angular, services and interfaces usually act as the Model.
ğŸ‘‰ Example: A service that fetches user data from an API.
ğŸ”¹ 2. View
View represents the User Interface (UI).
It includes:HTML,CSS,Buttons,Forms
In Angular, the component template (.html file) is the View.
ğŸ‘‰ Example: A form where the user enters their name.
ğŸ”¹ 3. ViewModel
ViewModel connects the Model and View.
In Angular, the Component (.ts file) acts as the ViewModel.
It contains: Variables,Functions,Logic
It controls what data is shown in the View.
ğŸ”„ How Data Works in MVVM (Angular)
The Model provides data.
The Component (ViewModel) processes it.
The View displays it.
With two-way data binding (ngModel):
If data changes in UI â†’ it updates in component.

Que 39) What are Angular Lifecycle Hooks?
--------------------------------------------
Lifecycle hooks are special methods in Angular that run at different stages of a componentâ€™s life.
Just like a human life has stages (birth â†’ growth â†’ work â†’ death),
a component also has stages (created â†’ updated â†’ destroyed).
Angular gives us hooks to run code at these stages.
ğŸ“Œ Main Lifecycle Hooks (In Simple Words)
1ï¸âƒ£ ngOnChanges()
ğŸ‘‰ Runs when input data changes.
If a parent component sends new data to a child component, this method runs.
Used to react to input changes.
Simple meaning:
"When input value changes, do something."
2ï¸âƒ£ ngOnInit()
ğŸ‘‰ Runs once after the component is created.
Used to load data from API.
Used to initialize variables.
Simple meaning:
"Component is ready. Start your work."
3ï¸âƒ£ ngDoCheck()
ğŸ‘‰ Runs every time Angular checks for changes.
Used for custom change detection.
Runs very frequently.
Simple meaning:
"Angular is checking for updates."
4ï¸âƒ£ ngAfterContentInit()
ğŸ‘‰ Runs once after external content is added.
When content is passed using <ng-content>.
Simple meaning:
"External content is now added."
5ï¸âƒ£ ngAfterContentChecked()
ğŸ‘‰ Runs every time external content is checked.
Simple meaning:
"Angular checked the external content."
6ï¸âƒ£ ngAfterViewInit()
ğŸ‘‰ Runs once after component view is loaded.
View = HTML template.
Used when accessing DOM elements.
Simple meaning:
"HTML is loaded. You can access it now."
7ï¸âƒ£ ngAfterViewChecked()
ğŸ‘‰ Runs every time the view is checked.
Simple meaning:
"Angular checked the HTML again."
8ï¸âƒ£ ngOnDestroy()
ğŸ‘‰ Runs just before the component is removed.
Used to unsubscribe observables.
Used to clear timers.
Simple meaning:
"Component is about to be deleted. Clean up."

Que 40) What is a Pipe in Angular?
-----------------------------------
A Pipe is used to change or format data before showing it on the screen.
ğŸ‘‰ It only changes how the data looks.
ğŸ‘‰ It does NOT change the original data.
ğŸ¯ Simple Meaning
A pipe is like a filter.
It takes data â†’ changes its format â†’ shows the updated result in the HTML.
ğŸ§  Example
Suppose you have:
name = "mahesh";
In HTML:
{{ name | uppercase }}
Output on screen:
MAHESH
But the original value is still:
mahesh
âœ” Only display changed
âŒ Original data not changed
ğŸ“Œ Built-in Pipes in Angular
1ï¸âƒ£ Uppercase Pipe
{{ name | uppercase }}
Makes text CAPITAL.
2ï¸âƒ£ Date Pipe
{{ today | date }}
Formats date nicely.
3ï¸âƒ£ Currency Pipe
{{ price | currency }}
Formats number as money.
4ï¸âƒ£ Lowercase Pipe
{{ name | lowercase }}
Makes text small letters.

Que 41) What is Angular Universal?
------------------------------------
Angular Universal is a way to run your Angular app on the server first, instead of only in the browser.
Normally:
Angular runs in the browser.
The browser downloads JavaScript.
Then the page loads.
With Angular Universal:
The server prepares the full HTML page first.
Then sends it to the browser.
So the page appears faster.
ğŸ§  Simple Meaning
ğŸ‘‰ Normal Angular â†’ Browser builds the page.
ğŸ‘‰ Angular Universal â†’ Server builds the page first.
ğŸš€ Why Do We Use It?
1ï¸âƒ£ Faster First Load
User sees the page quickly.
2ï¸âƒ£ Better SEO
Search engines (Google) can easily read the content.
3ï¸âƒ£ Better Performance
Especially useful for:
E-commerce websites
Blogs
News websites
ğŸ“Œ Example
Without Angular Universal:
User opens website
Blank screen for 2â€“3 seconds
Then content appears
With Angular Universal:
User opens website
Content appears immediately
ğŸ”„ Real-Life Example
Imagine ordering food:
Normal Angular â†’ Restaurant cooks after you arrive.
Angular Universal â†’ Food is already prepared when you arrive.
So you get it faster ğŸ½ï¸

Que 42) How to Optimize Angular Applications?
---------------------------------------------
Optimizing means making your Angular app faster and smoother.
1ï¸âƒ£ Use AOT (Ahead-of-Time Compilation)
ğŸ‘‰ Angular converts code into browser-ready JavaScript before running the app.
Benefit:
Faster loading
Smaller app size
Fewer errors at runtime
Simple meaning:
Prepare everything early so the app starts faster.
2ï¸âƒ£ Lazy Loading
ğŸ‘‰ Load modules only when needed.
Example:
User opens Home page â†’ Only Home loads
User clicks Admin page â†’ Then Admin loads
Benefit:
Faster first load
Smaller initial bundle
Simple meaning:
Donâ€™t load everything at once.
3ï¸âƒ£ OnPush Change Detection
ğŸ‘‰ Angular checks for changes only when necessary.
Benefit:
Fewer checks
Better performance
Simple meaning:
Donâ€™t check everything again and again.
4ï¸âƒ£ Tree Shaking
ğŸ‘‰ Remove unused code automatically during build.
Benefit:
Smaller file size
Simple meaning:
Delete unused code before sending to browser.
5ï¸âƒ£ Minification & Compression
ğŸ‘‰ Remove spaces, shorten variable names, compress files.
Benefit:
Smaller download size
Faster loading
Simple meaning:
Make files smaller.
6ï¸âƒ£ Use trackBy with ngFor
ğŸ‘‰ Helps Angular identify which items changed in a list.
Without trackBy:
Angular reloads entire list.
With trackBy:
Angular updates only changed items.
Simple meaning:
Update only what changed.
7ï¸âƒ£ Use Service Workers
ğŸ‘‰ Cache files for offline use.
Benefit:
Faster reload
Works even without internet (PWA)
Simple meaning:
Save data locally for faster access.

Que 43) What are Angular Interceptors?
--------------------------------------
Angular Interceptors are special services that sit between your app and the server.
A central place to control all HTTP requests and responses.
They can: Check,Modify, Or handle HTTP requests and responses
before they reach the server or come back to your app.
ğŸ‘‰ Interceptor = Middle person between Angular and Backend.
When you send a request:
App â†’ Interceptor â†’ Server
When response comes:
Server â†’ Interceptor â†’ App
ğŸ¯ Why Do We Use Interceptors?
1ï¸âƒ£ Add Authentication Token
Automatically add JWT token to every request.
Example:
Authorization: Bearer token
No need to add it manually every time.
2ï¸âƒ£ Handle Errors Globally
If server returns error (like 401 or 500),
you can handle it in one place.
3ï¸âƒ£ Logging
Log all requests and responses.
4ï¸âƒ£ Show Loader
Start loading spinner when request starts,
stop when response comes.
ğŸ“Œ Real-Life Example
Think of an interceptor like a security guard at office gate:
Every person (request) must pass through the guard.
Guard checks ID (token).
Guard allows or blocks entry.
Guard can also record entry details (logging).

Que 44) What is NgZone in Angular?
----------------------------------
NgZone is a service that helps Angular know
ğŸ‘‰ â€œSomething changed, update the screen!â€
Angular needs to know when to refresh the UI.
NgZone helps Angular track async operations like:
setTimeout(), setInterval(),HTTP requests,Button clicks, Promises
ğŸ§  Simple Meaning
NgZone = Angularâ€™s monitoring system
It watches for background work.
When that work finishes, it tells Angular:
â€œNow update the view.â€
ğŸ“Œ Why Is It Needed?
Angular updates the UI using change detection.
But when async tasks run (like API calls), Angular must know when they finish.
NgZone helps Angular detect that and refresh the screen.
ğŸ¯ Example
Suppose:
