Que 47) How do you use Typed Forms? 
----------------------------------------------------
In Angular 19, Typed Forms make Reactive Forms safer and easier to use by adding proper data types.
Earlier, form values were treated like any type (anything could go inside).
Now, Angular lets you define exactly what type of data each form field should have â€” like string, number, or boolean.
âœ… What does that mean in simple words?
Typed Forms help you:
âœ” Catch mistakes while writing code (before running the app)
âœ” Avoid runtime errors
âœ” Get better auto-suggestions in VS Code
âœ” Make large forms easier to manage
ğŸ§  Example (Without Typed Form)
profileForm = new FormGroup({
  name: new FormControl(''),
  age: new FormControl(0)
});
Here, Angular does not strictly check types.
ğŸ§  Example (With Typed Form in Angular 19)
profileForm = new FormGroup<{
  name: FormControl<string>;
  age: FormControl<number>;
}>({
  name: new FormControl(''),
  age: new FormControl(0)
});
Now:
name must always be a string
age must always be a number
If you try to assign wrong data, TypeScript will show an error immediately
ğŸ¯ Why is this useful?
Imagine a big form like:
Registration form
Banking form
Loan application form
Typed Forms:
Prevent wrong data types
Make your code cleaner
Help other developers understand your form structure easily
ğŸ“Œ In One Line
Typed Forms in Angular 19 make reactive forms type-safe, safer, and easier to manage by defining exact data types for each form control.

Que 48) What is the purpose of the Signal API? 
-----------------------------------------------
The Signal API in Angular is a new and easier way to manage data (state) in your application.
In simple words ğŸ‘‰
A Signal is a special variable that automatically updates the UI whenever its value changes.
ğŸ§  Why do we need it?
In older Angular versions:
We used @Input(), @Output(), BehaviorSubject, or manual change detection.
Sometimes we had to manage updates manually.
With Signals, Angular automatically:
Tracks changes
Updates only the necessary parts of the screen
Improves performance
âœ… Simple Example
import { signal } from '@angular/core';
count = signal(0);
increase() {
  this.count.set(this.count() + 1);
}
In HTML:
<p>{{ count() }}</p>
<button (click)="increase()">Increase</button>
ğŸ‘‰ When you click the button:
The signal value changes
Angular automatically updates the UI
No manual change detection needed
ğŸ¯ What Signals Do for You
âœ” Automatically track data changes
âœ” Automatically update the view
âœ” Reduce complex RxJS code
âœ” Improve performance
âœ” Make state management easier

Que 49) How does the inject() function work?
----------------------------------------------
The inject() function in Angular is a new and easier way to get services (dependencies) without writing them inside the constructor.
ğŸ§  First, what is Dependency Injection (DI)?
In Angular, when a component needs a service (like HttpClient or a custom service), we normally inject it using the constructor.
Example (Old way):
