userService = inject(UserService);
Thatâ€™s it!
No constructor needed.
ğŸ¯ Why is this useful?
âœ” Cleaner code
âœ” No need to write constructor just for injection
âœ” Useful in standalone components
âœ” Can be used inside functions, guards, interceptors, etc.
ğŸ“Œ Simple Difference
Old way:
constructor(private service: MyService) {}
New way:
service = inject(MyService);
Both do the same thing â€” but inject() makes it shorter and cleaner.
ğŸ“Œ In One Line
The inject() function allows you to get services directly without using constructor injection, making your Angular code simpler and cleaner.

