Que 58) Difference between Template-driven Forms and Reactive Forms ?
------------------------------------------------------------------------
Angular provides two ways to create forms:
ğŸ”¹ Template-driven Forms
ğŸ‘‰ Form logic is written mostly in the HTML template.
Simple meaning:
You create and control the form inside the HTML.
Angular automatically handles most of the work.
Best for:
âœ” Small and simple forms (like login, contact form)
Features:
Uses Angular directives like ngModel
Supports two-way data binding
Easier to write
Less code in TypeScript
ğŸ”¹ Reactive Forms
ğŸ‘‰ Form logic is written in the TypeScript file (component class).
Simple meaning:
You create the form manually in TypeScript.
You have full control over validation and form behavior.
Best for:
âœ” Large and complex forms (like registration with many validations)
Features:
Form is created explicitly using FormControl, FormGroup
Works in a synchronous and predictable way
More control and better for complex validation
Uses an immutable data model


Que 59) What are Angular Guards?
--------------------------------
Angular Guards are used to control access to pages (routes) in an Angular application.
ğŸ‘‰ In simple words:
Guards act like a security check before opening a page.
They decide:
Whether a user can open a page
Whether a user can leave a page
Whether a module can be loaded
ğŸ” Why do we use Guards?
To:
Protect pages from unauthorized users
Stop users from leaving a page accidentally
Control navigation in the application
ğŸ“Œ Common Types of Guards
ğŸ”¹ 1. CanActivate
ğŸ‘‰ Checks if a user can open a route.
Example:
Only logged-in users can open the Dashboard page.
If not logged in â†’ access denied.
ğŸ”¹ 2. CanDeactivate
ğŸ‘‰ Checks if a user can leave a route.
Example:
If a form is not saved, it asks:
â€œAre you sure you want to leave?â€
ğŸ”¹ 3. CanLoad
ğŸ‘‰ Checks if a lazy-loaded module can be loaded.
Example:
Only admin users can load the Admin module.
ğŸ¯ Simple Example
Think of Guards like a security guard in a building:
CanActivate â†’ Checks ID before entering.
CanDeactivate â†’ Asks before exiting.
CanLoad â†’ Checks permission before opening a restricted floor.

Que 60) How do you create custom validators in Angular?
---------------------------------------------------------
ğŸ‘‰ A custom validator is used when built-in validators (like required, minLength) are not enough.
In simple words:
A custom validator is just a function that checks something and:
Returns error if invalid
Returns null if valid
ğŸ§  Why do we need it?
Example:
Check if username already exists
Check if password is strong
Check if age is above 18
These validations are not available by default, so we create our own.
ğŸ”¹ Simple Steps (Reactive Forms)
Step 1: Create a Validator Function
import { AbstractControl, ValidationErrors, ValidatorFn } from '@angular/forms';
export function usernameValidator(): ValidatorFn {
  return (control: AbstractControl): ValidationErrors | null => {
    const forbiddenUsernames = ['admin', 'test', 'user'];
    if (forbiddenUsernames.includes(control.value)) {
      return { usernameTaken: true };   // âŒ Invalid
    }
    return null;   // âœ… Valid
  };
}
ğŸ‘‰ If username is "admin" â†’ error
ğŸ‘‰ Otherwise â†’ valid
Step 2: Use It in Form Control
this.myForm = this.fb.group({
  username: ['', [usernameValidator()]]
});
ğŸ” How It Works (Simple)
User enters username
Validator function runs
If username is not allowed â†’ shows error
If valid â†’ form works normally
ğŸ¯ In one line:
A custom validator in Angular is a function that checks your own validation rules and returns an error if the input is invalid.

